  "title": "Struktureller Wandel",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "e9508590e2820a8a",
      "text": "# Struktureller Wandel: Die Poesie der Reformen und die Realität der Evolution"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "723e54e9ecc5f55b",
      "text": "The concept of change has a useful vagueness in some respects. It is probably generally accepted today that change cannot be understood as a return to an equilibrium (old or new). But this still leaves open whether change is intentional or whether it simply happens. It also remains open whether, if brought about intentionally, it conforms (more or less) to intentions or not; and whether, if not planned, it is noticed before it happens, while it is happening, or only after it has happened. Broad-based research on transformations in organizations, still under the impression of the distinction between formal and informal organization, has led to the insight that a transformation succeeds if it manages to overcome resistance to change and to achieve acceptance. However, this does not achieve much more than turning a paradox into a tautology. The transformation paradox (the organization is the same in different states) is reformulated as a tautology: it succeeds when it succeeds. Such reformulation is meaningful only if it opens access to conditions of acceptance, that is, if it proposes and verifies conditioning. And it is not enough to arrive at purely \"biographical\" solutions, i.e. to say: this varies from case to case and depends on the history or culture of the system in question."
    },
    {
      "type": "pagefold",
      "id": "a00ef373caaab999",
      "text": "~"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "49cd2d451e0e91bf",
      "text": "\nLUHMANN, Niklas, 2000. Struktureller Wandel: Die Poesie der Reformen und die Realität der Evolution. In: LUHMANN, Niklas, Organisation und Entscheidung. Online. Wiesbaden: VS Verlag für Sozialwissenschaften. p. 330–360. [Accessed 24 July 2022]. ISBN 978-3-322-97094-7. \n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "b91d04abadc0229c",
      "text": "p. 357n65 Vgl. E.D. Cope, The Primary Factors of Organic Evolution, Chicago 1896, S. 172 H.; Elman R. Service, The Law of Evolutionary Potential, in: Marshall D. Sahlins/Elman R. Service (Hrsg.), Evolution and Culture, Ann Arbor Mich. 1960, S. 93 H. Heute ist wohl unbestritten, dass \"Cope's rule\" nicht ohne Einschränkung gilt. Es gibt auch evolutionäre Spezifikationen, die dem Aufbau höherer Komplexität dienen. Siehe z.B. G. Ledyard Stebbins, The Basis of Progressive Evolution, Chapel Hill N.C. 1969, insb. S. 120 H. Aber hier handelt es sich um sehr seltene evolutionäre Erfindungen, während die normale Evolution mit Aufbau und Destruktion von Systemen arbeitet. Der Systemtypus Organisation selbst dürfte mit seinem Potenzial für Komplexität eine solche evolutionäre Erfindung sein. Dabei geht es aber eher um die Emergenz einer neuen Form für Autopoiesis und nicht um das normale Lernen/Verlernen von Strukturen in Organisationen, das im vorliegenden Zusammenhang interessiert."
    },
    {
      "type": "pagefold",
      "id": "8710b3222b2f31c0",
      "text": "EN"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "a7e720875c37c8ec",
      "text": "Today it is probably undisputed that \"Cope's rule\" does not hold without qualification. There are also evolutionary specifications that serve to build higher complexity. See, e.g., G. Ledyard Stebbins, The Basis of Progressive Evolution, Chapel Hill N.C. 1969, esp. p. 120 H. But here we are dealing with very rare evolutionary inventions, whereas normal evolution deals with construction and destruction of systems. The system type organization itself, with its potential for complexity, is likely to be such an evolutionary invention. But this is more about the emergence of a new form for autopoiesis and not about the normal learning/unlearning of structures in organizations, which is of interest in the present context."
    },
